<subSubSection id="46E76549FFEB543BAAE4FAA9BF73FBC1" pageId="4" pageNumber="369" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="0E4236C2FFEB543BAAE4FAA9BF73FBC1" blockId="4.[151,1437,440,1188]" pageId="4" pageNumber="369">
<emphasis id="3C89EAD0FFEB543BAAE4FAA9BA77FC51" bold="true" box="[199,322,908,935]" pageId="4" pageNumber="369">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Differs from two other members of the 
<emphasis id="3C89EAD0FFEB543BA92AFAA8B84EFC51" box="[777,891,909,935]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="369">chlorotica</emphasis>
group by smaller size. Differs from small green species from the 
<taxonomicName id="C9FD4D41FFEB543BAB74FA94BAFFFC3D" authorityName="Linnavuori" authorityYear="1978" box="[343,458,945,971]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Macropsis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="369" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="minuscula">
<emphasis id="3C89EAD0FFEB543BAB74FA94BAFFFC3D" box="[343,458,945,971]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="369">minuscula</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group by sharply angular head and anterior margin of pronotum, crown having almost the same length in the middle and next to eyes in dorsal view, and by strongly developed median keel on face, pro-, and mesonotum (
<figureCitation id="96C62A47FFEB543BAB79FADCB90CFBE5" box="[346,569,1017,1043]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–22" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1804,1829]" captionTargetBox="[161,1422,173,1777]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[151,1433,166,1785]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 1–22. 1–3—Macropsis simplex Jacobi, female (1—lateral view; 2—dorsal view; 3—face); 4–5—M. tincta Tisheсhkin sp. n., male (4—lateral view; 5—dorsal view); 6–12—M. tuberculata (Linnavuori), female (6–8—holotype, photos by Alyssa Seemann; 9–12—females from Ambo, Ethiopia; 6, 9—face and pronotum; 7, 10–11—lateral view; 8, 12—dorsal view); 13–15—M. viridofulgida Tisheсhkin sp. n., female (13—lateral view; 14—dorsal view; 15—face); 16–22—Macropsis hippodameia Linnavuori (16, 19—male, lateral view; 17, 21—same, face; 18, 20—same, dorsal view; 22—female, lateral view)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3772389" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3772389/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="369">Figs. 14 and 18, 20</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="96C62A47FFEB543BA866FADCB98FFBE5" box="[581,698,1017,1043]" captionStart="FIGURES 23–40" captionStartId="6.[151,264,1890,1915]" captionTargetBox="[161,1432,427,1865]" captionTargetId="figure@6.[151,1435,409,1871]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURES 23–40. 23–33—Macropsis nikippa Tisheсhkin sp. n. (23–24—dorsolateral view; 25, 31—lateral view; 26–27, 32— dorsal view; 28–30, 33—face; 23–30—male; 31–33—female); 34–40—M. antibia Tisheсhkin sp. n. (34, 36, 39–40—lateral view; 35—dorsal view; 37—dorsolateral view; 38—face; 34–38—male; 39–40—female)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3772391" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3772391/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="369">26–27, 32</figureCitation>
). Distinctly differs from other species by coloration. Also, distinguished among other species by very narrow 2 
<superScript id="F9889B8AFFEB543BA882FD39B984FBDC" attach="left" box="[673,689,1052,1066]" fontSize="6" pageId="4" pageNumber="369">nd</superScript>
valvulae with small preapical teeth.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="46E76549FFEB543BAAE4FD64BAB7FBAD" box="[199,386,1089,1115]" pageId="4" pageNumber="369" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph id="0E4236C2FFEB543BAAE4FD64BAB7FBAD" blockId="4.[151,1437,440,1188]" box="[199,386,1089,1115]" pageId="4" pageNumber="369">
<emphasis id="3C89EAD0FFEB543BAAE4FD64BA33FBAD" bold="true" box="[199,262,1089,1115]" pageId="4" pageNumber="369">Host.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="C9FD4D41FFEB543BAB2EFD64BA6EFBAD" box="[269,347,1089,1115]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fabaceae" genus="Acacia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Fabales" pageId="4" pageNumber="369" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="3C89EAD0FFEB543BAB2EFD64BA6EFBAD" box="[269,347,1089,1115]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="369">Acacia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sp.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="46E76549FFEB543BAAE4FD40BA90FAA6" pageId="4" pageNumber="369" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="0E4236C2FFEB543BAAE4FD40BFE9FB55" blockId="4.[151,1437,440,1188]" pageId="4" pageNumber="369">
<emphasis id="3C89EAD0FFEB543BAAE4FD40BA7BFB89" bold="true" box="[199,334,1125,1151]" pageId="4" pageNumber="369">Etymology.</emphasis>
The name of the new species derives from a combination of Latin words “viridis” (green) and “fulgidus” (glittering, shining) and refers to bright green coloration and smooth and shiny cuticle.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="0E4236C2FFEB543BAAB4FDC8BA90FAA6" blockId="4.[151,1436,1261,1360]" pageId="4" pageNumber="369">
The 
<taxonomicName id="C9FD4D41FFEB543BAAEAFDC8BA09FAF1" authorityName="Linnavuori" authorityYear="1978" box="[201,316,1261,1287]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Macropsis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="369" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="minuscula">
<emphasis id="3C89EAD0FFEB543BAAEAFDC8BA09FAF1" box="[201,316,1261,1287]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="369">minuscula</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group. Small green, greyish green, or brown species, often with black pattern on head and pronotum, especially in males. Known species differ from each other by shape of penis, style tip and, partially, pygofer appendages (
<figureCitation id="96C62A47FFEB543BAB2CFC10BAADFAA6" box="[271,408,1333,1360]" captionStart="FIGURES 41–81" captionStartId="8.[151,264,1732,1757]" captionTargetBox="[258,1328,184,1711]" captionTargetId="figure@8.[256,1332,166,1712]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURES 41–81. 41–43—Macropsis simplex Jacobi; 44–48—M. tincta Tisheсhkin sp. n.; 49—M. chinai Metcalf; 50—M. kanongensis Evans; 51—M. capensis (Cogan); 52–55—M. tuberculata (Linnavuori); 56–58—M. turneri China; 59–62—M. viridofulgida Tisheсhkin sp. n.; 63–67— M. hippodameia Linnavuori; 68–70—M. minuscula Linnavuori; 71–72—M. bussaensis Linnavuori; 73–76—M. thargelia Linnavuori; 77–79—M. nigrosignata (Stål); 80–81—M. bitaeniata Linnavuori. 41–42, 55, 59–60—2nd valvulae of ovipositor; 43, 61–62—female 7th sternite; 44—male 2nd abdominal apodemes; 45, 49–51, 63–64, 68, 71, 73, 77, 80—penis, lateral view; 46—pygofer process, lateral view; 47—pygofer processes, back view; 48, 67, 70, 76, 79, 81—style; 52, 57—head, pro-, and mesonotum, dorsal view; 53, 56—forewing; 54, 58—female genital segments, ventral view; 65–66, 69, 72, 74–75, 78—style tip. 49–50, 63–81—after Linnavuori (1978), 51—after Theron (1970), 56–58—after China (1925)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3772393" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3772393/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="369">Figs. 63–81</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
